reviewBody: Conversations does it better than Seasons, depending on your tongue. For me it hits a little better. They are way more consistent in the service category, where I get actual words from the employees who work diligently in the kitchen. They also have a couple of superior options to Seasons across the street, however the size proportions and quality can be inconsistent. I think the one thing that has me most scratching my head is why they would decide to have it be a get & go only location. In summation, I think Conversations is still one of the weaker options, but at least you can always be serviced for get & go, unlike West Side Market.

author: Logan Reel
reviewBody: Unless you plan on living off pizza and pasta during your time here at Iowa state seasons marketplace is absolutely terrible, everything is deep fried and sodium loaded , for example the wood grill has ribs with 3,210 mg of sodium per serving . (Youre meant to consume 2000mg max a day) the food is very unappetizing and the menus are very often misleading, often having things listed not available, and the only thing that would be somewhat macro nutrient friendly the bonsias has been closed for 3 weeks straight. If youre planning on eating after 7 30 pm forget it , unless like I mentioned you would like to live off burned pizza and stale pasta. Its ridiculous that students pay a mandatory $2,000 for a meal plan for which most days has next to nothing nutritious. As a first year student I dont plan on returning next year to live on campus, I hope they are able to make some changes and idk maybe have things that are actually beneficial to someones health rather than attempting to give people kidney stones with the insane amounts of sodium in the food options .

author: Nathan Masters
reviewBody: Known by everyone as UDCC, this community center is packed with the amenities that supplement dorm life for the nearby Friley Hall, Helser Hall, Eaton Hall and Martin Hall. UDCC hosts the mail distribution center, office space, public restrooms, and three dining options. The main cafeteria is not open all the time but has a high capacity and good selection from many options. Clyde's has been newly renovated and provides a more compact feel, similar to a dine-in place. The C Store is like a gas station without the pumps, lots of snack food options and subs to go. All dining is compatible with the meal plan information stored on the Student ID, it's as easy as a swipe of your card. During my two years in Eaton Hall UDCC was a frequent lunch and supper stop for me. It is convenient to walk across the courtyard whenever I feel hungry, and it was good peace of mind to know I didn't have to worry about a package getting left out in the open, everything is processed through the mail desk and it is very secure. UDCC may often be busy and crowded during the lunch rush but it became an important part of my home away from home where I could meet up with friends, grab a bite, or dash out of the rain to wait for the bus. Take time to see what it can be for you

author: Zachary Fish
reviewBody: Best of the 3 dining halls on campus and it's not even close. Their butter chicken is easily my favorite thing I've ever eaten, and they also put out some incredible Italian meatballs, tikka masala, Chinese foods, and gyro meat, depending on the day. When they don't have any of that, there's usually some kind of rice or chicken available, and they also have pizza during all hours of operation that is WORLDS better than the crappy ones they make at Seasons/UDM. Finally, a variety of desserts including great ice cream 24/7 that's made by local farms and rotates flavors, from chocolate chip to coffee to sherbets to just plain old french vanilla. They're also happy to accomodate dietary needs or refill condiments, if you ask -- just as the other two dining halls are. Only drawback is that the late-night hours here (M-Th, 7:30-11:00 PM) offer less choices for obvious reasons, so always go earlier to avoid that if you want, or check the menu online first. Big ups to the ISU Dining team... you guys know what you're doing!!!

author: Benjamin Steward
reviewBody: Try Powermilk today - the power drink for the whole family! Powermilk is made from the finest Powerade and chocolate milk ISU dining has to offer. One sip of Powermilk will get you the power you need to get through the toughest challenge. Don't believe me? The first time I tried Powermilk, and I was able scale the Campanile, take a Calc III exam remotely and grab a a goose as it flew by, all before jumping down in front of a group of touring students. The man leading the group slowly turned, gave a little chuckle, and said "That's a lot of power!" I looked up past his bushy beard and saw that it was Steve Butler himself! He instantly gave me an A in not only Calc III, but in all the previous Calculus classes I had ever taken. Feeling powerful, I let go of the goose and galloped back to Friley Windows for another sip. After trying Powermilk, you will never need any other form of sustenance. That's the Powermilk Promise! Powermilk currently comes in two irresistible flavors - Blue-brown and Red-brown. They both taste as good as they sound, so grab a glass today!

author: Luke Becker
reviewBody: Tons of options here, but sometimes the dishes available are a bit different. However, I once had the "italian sausage and kale" soup here and it was probably the best dish I have had at any of the dining halls.

reviewBody: terrible place to eat. They literally served hot cheetoh dust with lasagna. Like who does that??
